#ElviePartner I love having the freedom of pumping wherever with @elvie wearable pumps while at my own rhythm with the new Pump with Elvie app update Smart Rhythms. I used and loved Elvie while breastfeeding my previous baby, but this update caters to my goals in a whole new way. I can select one of 3 different rhythms depending on my pumping goals and needs (and each breast can have it’s own separate rhythm, too). My favorite was Slow & Gentle the first few days as I was allowing healing after some bad latches caused some major pain. But now that I’m healing up, I’ve been able to enjoy the two other rhythms to maximize milk production and manage the heavier milk flow to keep this little guy’s belly full—all while not being tied up to the wall multiple times a day. Because life did not slow down after baby— and Elvie is one powerful tool that keeps me from missing a beat. Click the link in my bio to learn more! #TheRealFeed #ElviePump #ElviePartner

I woke up at 5:30 the morning of the 14th and had this overwhelming feeling ‘today is the day.’ 

When Cassian woke up we played for while and he covered my belly with kisses and hugs and belly bumps. My last moments with him being the baby of the family were so sweet.

I showered and got ready and took some last belly photos. 16 minutes later, as I sat in my desk chair with my family close by, my water broke.

We made our way to the hospital— from what happened in previous births, baby could be here as soon as 3 minutes later to two hours later. And this is my 4th, it should be quick, right?

I let the staff know I wanted zero medication, and I wanted to be left alone. I got exactly that. I was left to labor in peace and quiet with plenty of fluids and snacks, and it took a bit before contractions started once again and several hours before pain began to accompany the contractions. As the pain intensified, my focus on my breath increased. I walked, rocked, swayed, and even took naps. This baby was taking his time. 13 hours after my water broke, I called my nurse in and asked her if what was there was the baby’s head. (Yes!) She hurriedly got my OB, and it was just the 4 of us (nurse, OB, hubby & me) in a dimly lit room. My OB asks, how do you want to do this? Not on my back, I tell her. I got up on the bed and while squatting, Xavian was born in 3 pushes. My rainbow, my bright light had arrived ♡ 1.15.23 @ 01:58am

Imagine there is a bank account that credits your account each morning with $86,400. It carries over no balance from day to day. Every evening the bank deletes whatever part of the balance you failed to used during the day. What would you do? Draw out every cent, of course? Each of us has such a bank, it's name is time. Every morning, it credits you 86,400 seconds. Every night it writes off at a lost, whatever of this you failed to invest to a good purpose. It carries over no balance. It allows no over draft. Each day it opens a new account for you. Each night it burns the remains of the day. If you fail to use the day's deposits, the loss is yours. There is no drawing against "tomorrow". You must live in the present on today's deposits. Invest it so as to get from it the utmost in health, happiness, and health. The clock is running. Make the most of today.-Marc Levy

In case nobody has said this to you recently or ever, I hope you’re proud of yourself. They say too much pride will kill you. Maybe. But too little of it is just as true. We get caught up, and keep the right words tied down too tightly. Listen to me; if you’re doing the best you can with what you have, and you’re evolving, you’re fighting, and still full of fire and feeling, well, be proud of that. You could have turned back a long time ago. But you didn’t. Nobody will ever understand your path. The rough roads and weather were yours to travel through, and you likely traveled them alone. You deserve people in your life now who not only want to see you rise, but want to rise alongside you. You’re hard enough on yourself, please don’t extend a hand to someone who takes it, only to hold you down. Your sins are paid for, lessons learned, scars adorned, and you’re free to fall again. It’s the brokenhearted that piece themselves together. That’s the kind of strength you should be proud of, in case nobody has said that to you recently. Or ever. - J. Raymond

Jumping on mama and being all over the place ends up was phase that I didn’t realize I missed. It’s so short lived! In time their practice will evolve, so in the meantime I spend time bonding and sharing my love and patience with these tiny souls ❤️ 

@aloyoga

1. Save your lower back by arching through the entire spine. Lead with your heart and open up the chest to prevent pain in this pose. Imagine there being a string at your heart and it is pulling your chest upward.

2. If you have a hard time coming up and need some support, place each hand on your glutes (where your back pockets would be) to support your lower back as you come back up.

3. Also! Don’t rock back and forth. Get hips over knees. This will help prevent you from crunching into your lower back and allow you to practice opening up the chest.

Listen to your body and practice safely!

Mindful breathing has helped me in so many situations that I knew it was something I wanted to share with my children. Seeing my daughter walking around at 11 months old with her hands in prayer and breathing, and even breathing through boo boos at that age, showed me that they can have the ability to use the practice at such a young age.

Here’s some things I did and how you can teach your little one:

•Start by modeling deep breathing for your baby. Breathe in slowly through your nose and out through your mouth.
Once your child is paying attention, help them to copy your breathing. You can place your hand on their chest to help them feel the rise and fall of their breath.

•As your child gets older, you can start to introduce different breathing exercises. For example, you can have them breathe in for 4 counts, hold their breath for 1 count, and then breathe out for 4 counts.

•Breathing techniques are a great way to help your child self-soothe and regulate their emotions. They can be used in any situation, from when they’re feeling fussy to when they’re feeling scared or overwhelmed. Be sure to practice during these times!

•Be patient and consistent. It may take some time for your baby to learn how to breathe deeply and slowly.

•Make it fun! You can turn breathing exercises into a game or sing a song about breathing.

•Be a role model. The more you breathe deeply and slowly, the more likely your baby is to do the same.

With a little practice, your child will be able to use breathing techniques to calm themselves down and cope with difficult emotions. And the earlier this is introduced into their lives, the more it becomes second nature to them.

I hope this helps!
